<h3>Tips</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Use the generated layout as a starting point, but tweak as needed. It will sometimes be necessary to space out buildings. Try to maintain the overall layout in terms of open/closed space as generated for more interesting / dynamic games.</li>
  <li>In general, the red side will have a terrain advantage. This is by design. Remember to design one side with slightly better position.</li>
  <li>If there is a large gap in the middle that both players want to fill, make sure to put blocking terrain at the halfway point to avoid giving either side an advantage. Consider using a <a href="http://infinitythewiki.com/en/Poor_Visibility_Zone" target="_blank">Poor Visibility Zone</a> to maintain the openness while providing some cover.</li>
  <li>Special terrain will likely function best as <a href="http://infinitythewiki.com/en/Poor_Visibility_Zone" target="_blank">Poor Visibility</a> (-6 MOD) or <a href="http://infinitythewiki.com/en/Zero_Visibility_Zone" target="_blank">Zero Visibility Zone</a> zones. You can spice that up by also making it <a href="http://infinitythewiki.com/en/Difficult_Terrain" target="_blank">Difficult Terrain</a> so that specialized troops can benefit. If only one player has Multiterrain troops, consider making it that type. If both players have Multiterrain, choose randomly among the supported types.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Things to Consider When Tweaking</h3>
<ol>
<li>Is a sniper position strong but not too dominant? It should not cover the entire table and should have at least one blind spot.</li>
<li>If a side has a tactical advantage, are there weaknesses for objectives or airborne deployment?</li>
<li>How many orders will each side have to spend to approach objectives, and is that balanced among other factors?</li>
<li>Are there areas on the board that support long range, midrange, and close-range engagements?</li>
<li>Does the layout support movement skills like superjump and climbing plus?</li>
</ol>


